<center>
<br>
<h2>John David Stone</h2>
Lecturer in Computer Science and Philosophy <br>
Manager of the <!WA1><a href="http://www.math.grin.edu/mathlan.html">Mathematics
Local-Area Network<a><br>
<!WA2><a href="http://www.math.grin.edu/">Department of Mathematics and
Computer Science</a><br>
<!WA3><A HREF="http://www.grin.edu/">Grinnell College</A><br>
Grinnell, Iowa 50112<br>
(515) 269-3181<br>
<!WA4><a href="http://www.math.grin.edu/science.jpg">Bowen Hall of Science</a>,
office 2418<br>
<!WA5><a href="mailto:stone@math.grin.edu">stone@math.grin.edu</a><br>
<br clear=left>
</center>

<p><hr><p>

Interests: syntax and semantics of programming languages, formal
language theory, computational linguistics, philosophy of language,
mathematical logic, automata theory, data structures, ontology, history of
philosophy, and set theory. <P>

This fall I'll be teaching one course, <!WA6><A
HREF="http://www.math.grin.edu/~stone/courses/fundamentals/">``Fundamentals of computer science
II,''</A> and conducting an independent study on artificial
intelligence.<P>

In the several <!WA7><a href="http://www.math.grin.edu/~stone/positions-held.html">positions I've held</a>, I've
taught <!WA8><a href="http://www.math.grin.edu/~stone/courses-taught.html">a wide variety of courses and
workshops</a> and published <!WA9><a href="http://www.math.grin.edu/~stone/publications.html">miscellaneous
papers, etc.</a>, on topics that caught my interest.  To see how I prepared
for my career in academia, you might want to have a look at my <!WA10><a
href="http://www.math.grin.edu/~stone/education.html">educational background</a>. <P>

I'm the principal investigator for a three-year study (1994-97) entitled
``In-class experiential learning in four fundamental courses,'' funded by a
<!WA11><A HREF="http://www.math.grin.edu/mathlan/NSF-proposal.ps">grant</A> from the Instrumentation and
Laboratory Improvement Program of the National Science Foundation. <P>

At Grinnell, I'm the chair of the <!WA12><a
href="http://www.grin.edu/~lingweb/">Linguistics Concentration
Committee</a> and of the <!WA13><A HREF="http://www.math.grin.edu/~stone/academic-computing/">Academic Computing
Committee</A>, I'm a member of the Selection Committee for the Robert
N. Noyce Prize Program, and I organize the <!WA14><A HREF="http://www.math.grin.edu/~stone/events/eplsg">Exotic
Programming Languages Study Group</A>. <P>

Here are some of the professional organizations that I belong to: <P>

<ul>
<li> <!WA15><a href="http://www.acm.org/"> Association for Computing Machinery</a>
<li> <!WA16><a href="http://www.acm.org/sigplan/">
ACM Special Interest Group on Programming Languages</a>
<li> Society for Exact Philosophy
<li> <!WA17><a href="http://cpsr.org/home"> Computer Professionals for Social
Responsibility</a>
<li> <!WA18><a href="http://www.maa.org/"> Mathematical Association of America</a>
<li> <!WA19><a href="http://e-math.ams.com/"> American Mathematical Society</a>
<li> <!WA20><A HREF="http://www.ucsusa.org/">Union of Concerned Scientists</A>
</ul>
<p>

I keep <!WA21><a href="http://www.math.grin.edu/~stone/startup-page.html">a collection of links</a> that I use
as my Netscape startup page, but its contents are somewhat arbitrary.
Persons who are curious about my inner life will find more reliable clues
in my <!WA22><a href="http://www.math.grin.edu/~stone/misc/recommended-reading.html">recommended-reading
list</a>. <P>

I invite correspondents to use my <!WA23><A HREF="http://www.math.grin.edu/~stone/misc/pgp-public-key.txt">PGP
public key</A> for confidential messages.  Call, write, or visit to obtain
a confirming sixteen-byte fingerprint. <P>

